<TEXT>
<TIMEX2 val="PAST_REF" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="2000-10-06T20:02:41.95" anchor_dir="BEFORE" comment="">Former</TIMEX2> U.S. representative Sidney Yates has died. When he retired
<TIMEX2 val="1999" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">last year</TIMEX2>, he was the oldest and longest serving member of the
house. NPR's Sheryl Corley reports from Chicago. 
<TURN>
Sidney Yates was first elected to the U.S. house in <TIMEX2 val="1948" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">1948</TIMEX2>, when Harry
Truman was President and for <TIMEX2 val="P4DE" mod="MORE_THAN" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="1948" anchor_dir="STARTING" comment="context allows more specific anchor_val">more than 4 decades</TIMEX2> he trounced every
challenger to face him in congressional election. He sat out <TIMEX2 val="" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">1 term</TIMEX2>
after losing a U.S. Senate race in <TIMEX2 val="196" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">the 1960s</TIMEX2>. But for <TIMEX2 val="" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">24 terms</TIMEX2>,
Yates represented Chicago's Northern Lake front in northern suburbs.
The congressman was known as a fervent liberal and supporter of the
arts and he was noted for his success in getting congress to finance
for national endowment for the art. In <TIMEX2 val="1993" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">1993</TIMEX2>, Yates was awarded a
Presidential Citizens Medal for his efforts. Yates was born in
Chicago and he was one of the few politicians who successfully
walked the tight rope between the Chicago machine and its
independent critics. He died <TIMEX2 val="2000-10-05" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">yesterday</TIMEX2> of renal failure and
complications from pneumonia. Sheryl Corley, NPR news, Chicago. 
</TEXT>
